--- !u!114 &181457933
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 181457932}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 6e642fb9836d71f48ae36d12307fc070, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  textComponent: {fileID: 24814796}
  storyScreens:
  - 'This Interactive Digital Narrative is part of a university research project
    conducted by Robert Gatt and Supervised by Mr. Jonathan Barbara.


    The project
    explores to what extent Interactive Digital Narratives can foster historical
    empathy, particularly towards multiple sides involved in a historical conflict.
    The experience may present perspectives, decisions, and outcomes that reflect
    the complexities and moral tensions of warfare.


    During the experience,
    you will be asked to complete questionnaires related to your perceptions and
    emotional responses. Please answer these honestly and to the best of your ability.
    There are no right or wrong answers.


    No personal data is collected.

    Your
    responses are anonymous and will be used solely for academic research purposes.


    By
    continuing, you confirm that you understand the nature of this project and consent
    to participate.'
  - 'In May 1565, the calm Maltese sea darkened with hundreds of sails. The Ottoman
    armada, sent by Sultan Suleiman the Magnificent, carried thousands of Janissaries,
    cavalry, and siege weapons, all bound for Malta. Their drums rolled like thunder,
    echoing across the coast.


    Grand Master Jean de Valette called every man,
    woman, and child to prepare. Slaves and free men alike fortified the walls of
    Birgu and Senglea, farmers abandoned their fields to take refuge behind stone
    battlements. Crops gathered early and wells poisioned.  Nothing was left for
    the enemy.  The island braced for the storm to come.'
  - "\u017Bejtun, your home, was among the first to burn. The Ottomans landed in
    Marsaxlokk, sweeping through fields and homes with fire and steel. You tried
    to flee with your family, but the soldiers came too fast. Screams filled the
    air as the village turned to smoke and ruin.\n\nHidden among the bushes, you
    waited until the sounds of battle faded. By dawn, everything you knew was gone."
  - 'You followed the fleeing crowds north until you reached Birgu, where Grand Master
    de Valette and the Knights of St. John prepared to defend the island. The walls
    shook with cannon fire from the sea, and the sky glowed red above Fort St. Elmo,
    where men fought and fell each day.


    Too young to fight, you offered to
    help however you could. The defenders put you on a boat and you headed towards
    the Fort under siege, Fort St. Elmo.'
  - "At night, as you were resting in your chambers, you swore you heard faint meows
    among the ruins. Some said it was the wind; others spoke of a small cat with
    a torn ear darting between the broken walls. \n\nWhether it was real or a trick
    of memory, you couldn\u2019t tell. But even in the midst of siege and death,
    that hope was enough to keep you moving.  This is your story, will you help in
    the fort, or will you loiok for your cat?"
  storyContinueButtons:
  - Start the Story
  - "You watched from afar, wondering if the ships would reach your village\u2026"
  - "You ran in fear of your life, leaving the your slain family behind\u2026"
  - "You found shelter among the knights, but your heart stayed restless\u2026"
  - "You began your search once more \u2014 for the cat, and for what remained of
    home."
  delay: 0.05
  continueButton: {fileID: 1949886302}
  continueButtonTMP: {fileID: 48706972}
  fortStElmoScene: 2
